# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1879-cincinnati-reds-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1876 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] It was the team's first season of existence, having been formed as part of the brand new National League in 1876.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] This team was not related (except by name) to the previous Cincinnati Red Stockings National Association team, which had folded in 1870.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] One bright spot for the Reds was the play of Charley Jones, who led the club with a batting average of .286, had the second highest home run total in the league with four, and was among the league leaders in doubles and slugging percentage.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds played their first ever game on April 25, 1876, defeating the St.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] Louis Brown Stockings 2–1 at Avenue Grounds.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] Wins would be few and far between for the Reds, as after putting up a solid 3–2 record in their opening five games, the Reds would go on an eleven-game losing streak to fall to 3–13.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] After defeating the Hartford Dark Blues 8–2 to end their losing streak, the Reds would then have a thirteen-game losing streak, and saw their record fall to 4–26.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] By the time the season was finished, Cincinnati had the worst record in the National League, as they ended the season with a 9–56 record, 42.5 games behind the first place Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1877 Cincinnati Reds season** was the team's second season in the National League.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished sixth and last in the league with a record of 15–42, 25½ games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] After finishing dead last in the National League in the 1876 season, the Reds attempted to improve their club by signing Lip Pike, who spent the previous season with the St.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Pike was also named the manager of the team.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds got off to another terrible start, as they had a 3–11 start to the season, and Pike stepped down as the manager.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The team was briefly disbanded by owner Josiah Keck, and although a group of eight businessmen stepped in to rescue the franchise, some Cincinnati players had been signed by other teams in the interim, and some newspapers subsequently refused to list the Red's results.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Bob Addy took over as player manager; however, he too saw very few wins as Cincinnati went 5–19 during his managerial stint.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Jack Manning then finished the year as player-manager, going 7–12, as the Reds had a 15–42 record and once again finished in the National League cellar, 25.5 games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Charley Jones had another solid season for the Reds, hitting .310 with two homers and a team high 36 RBI.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Manning also had a solid year, hitting .317, as he had a team high 80 hits while tying Jones with a team high 36 RBI.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Pike hit .298 with a team high four home runs, and added 23 RBI.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, rookie Bobby Mitchell came up late in the season and was very impressive, leading Cincinnati with six victories and a team best 3.51 ERA in twelve games.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1878 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished second in the National League with a record of 37–23, four games behind the Boston Red Caps.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] After finishing their first two seasons in the National League in last place, the Reds were hoping for some improvement in the 1878 season.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati signed Cal McVey of the Chicago White Stockings to become the team's new third baseman, and new manager.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Catcher Deacon White of the Boston Red Caps signed with Cincinnati.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White led the National League with a .387 batting average, 103 hits, eleven triples, 49 RBI, and a .545 slugging percentage with the Red Caps in 1877.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White also led the National League with 60 RBI while playing for the White Stockings in 1876.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, 23-year-old Will White was signed by the Reds.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White appeared in three games with the Boston Red Caps in 1877, going 2–1 with a 3.00 ERA.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Charley Jones had another very solid season with the Reds, as he had a .310 batting average, along with a team high three home runs and 39 RBI.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White saw his production slip, however, he still hit .314 with 29 RBI.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Player-manager McVey was solid with a .306 average and two home runs along with 28 RBI.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White had a spectacular season, going 30–21 with a 1.79 ERA in 468 innings pitched.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds opened the season with a six-game winning streak, and stayed hot in their first twenty games, going 15–5, and were sitting in first place in the National League.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati then went on a six-game losing streak, falling to 15–11, and out of first place.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds never reclaimed first place; however, they finished the season strong, including a nine-game winning streak late in the year, to finish in second place with a 37–23 record, five games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-boston-red-caps-season] The **1879 Boston Red Caps season** was the ninth season of the franchise.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-buffalo-bisons-season] The 1879 season was the debut year in the National League for the **Buffalo Bisons**, who had previously played an independent schedule.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-buffalo-bisons-season] The Bisons wound up with a record of 46–32 and finished in third place.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1879 Chicago White Stockings season** was the eighth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fourth in the National League and the second at Lakefront Park.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fourth in the National League with a record of 46–33.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1879 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished fifth in the National League with a record of 43–37, 14 games behind the Providence Grays.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds were hoping to build off a great 1878 season, in which the team finished in second place in the National League with a 37–23 record.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] In the off-season, the Reds announced that catcher Deacon White would become the player-manager.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati signed Ross Barnes to play shortstop.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Barnes had missed most of the 1877 season and all of the 1878 season after falling ill.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] In his last full season in 1876, Barnes played with the Chicago White Stockings, and led the NL with a .429 batting average, 138 hits, 126 runs, 38 doubles, and fourteen triples.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] King Kelly had a very solid season, hitting .348 with two home runs and 47 RBI, while another youngster, twenty-year-old Buttercup Dickerson, hit .291 with two home runs and a team high 57 RBI.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Deacon White rebounded from a poor 1878 season by his standards, as he hit .330 with a homer and 52 RBI.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, Will White led the NL with 75 starts, as he had a 43–31 record with a 1.99 ERA in his league high 680 innings pitched.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati started off hot, as they opened the season with a five-game winning streak.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] However, the club lost seven of their next eight games to fall under .500.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati had a mediocre 9–9 record after eighteen games, and player-manager Deacon White turned over his managerial duties to Cal McVey, who had been the Reds' player-manager in 1878.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati lost the first five games under McVey, however, the team began to play better, and ended the season with a 43–37 record, fifth in the league, and fourteen games behind the first-place Grays.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cleveland-blues-season] The 1879 season was the National League debut for the **Cleveland Blues**.
[src:1879-cincinnati-reds-season/1879-cleveland-blues-season] They finished the season 27–55, sixth in the eight-team National League.
